# User-Facing UI Copy

Product UI speaks to potential end users of the site, not to developers, admins, or security reviewers.

## Do not surface in UI

Never put these in user-facing strings (locales, flash, ERB labels, button status text, empty states, tooltips, emails to users):

- Cryptography or lock internals (tlock, drand, age, rounds, layers, ciphertext, blobs, keys, decrypt/encrypt jargon)
- Infrastructure or privilege details (admin access, database, S3, server, purge, plaintext)
- Library/framework/ops wording (crypto library, fetch blob, nested re-tlock, API)
- Threat-model reassurances aimed at engineers (e.g. "even with admin or database access")

## Prefer product language

Describe outcomes the user cares about:

- Locked until the timer ends / countdown finishes
- Original unavailable until unlock
- Extending the timer
- Permanent delete with no recovery
- Generic progress: "Starting…", "Securing your photo…", "Unlocking…"

## Where technical detail belongs

Implementation and threat-model notes go in code comments, PR descriptions, specs, and developer chat — never in `config/locales` product copy or visible UI.

When editing locales for features that use crypto or privileged storage, rewrite status/hint/lead strings so a non-technical user understands them without knowing how the system works.
